Note:
This file implements TIER 3 (Owned Heap) higher-level allocation wrappers
for the Runa runtime memory system.

OWNED HEAP WRAPPERS - Composable Helpers Over MemoryLayout.allocate
- Process zero-initialized owned-heap allocations
- Process strictly-aligned owned-heap allocations (with back-pointer header)
- Process owned-heap deallocation for back-pointer aligned allocations
- Provide a registry-aware size query for live owned-heap allocations

This file is essential because of the following reasons:
- Zero-initialized allocation is the natural shape for structure-shaped data
  that must start blank; rolling it into the core allocator would force every
  caller to pay the memset cost even when they immediately overwrite, so we
  expose it as a composable wrapper.
- Aligned allocation supports buffer alignment for executable formats,
  cache-line packing, and SIMD-friendly buffers. The MemoryLayout.allocate
  contract only guarantees 8-byte alignment; this wrapper synthesises stronger
  alignment by over-allocating and storing a back-pointer header.
- The registry-aware size query is the correct way to ask "how big is the
  user data behind this pointer?" - layout.runa's header carries a total_size
  (header plus user) so the user portion is only obtainable through the
  registry. This wrapper hides that detail from callers.

This file consists of the following functions/features/operation types:
- allocate_zeroed (size) - allocate then memory_zero
- allocate_aligned (size, alignment) - allocate with back-pointer header
- deallocate_aligned (ptr) - free back-pointer aligned allocation
- owned_heap_get_size (ptr) - registry-aware user-data size lookup

Migration history:
- 2026-05-18: Moved from compiler/internal/memory_utils.runa into the runtime
  tree per the CEO-ratified "memory management lives in runtime/core/memory/"
  ruling. The internal call to align_pointer_up (which was a duplicate of the
  canonical PointerPrimitive.pointer_align_up) was rewritten to use the
  canonical primitive directly during the move. The owned_heap_get_size
  function (formerly get_allocation_size) was rewritten from a fictitious
  size-header read to a registry-lookup against MemoryLayout's allocation
  registry, fixing a latent silent bug that the migration plan flagged.

Dependencies:
- Imports compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa for the canonical
  TIER-3 allocate/deallocate entrypoints and the registry_lookup helper used
  by owned_heap_get_size.
- Imports compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa for memory_zero
  (zeroed allocation) and memory_set_pointer / memory_get_pointer /
  memory_get_int64 (back-pointer header writes and registry reads).
- Imports compiler/frontend/primitives/core/pointer_primitive.runa for the
  canonical pointer_align_up used during aligned allocation.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as MemoryLayout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as MemoryCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/pointer_primitive.runa" as PointerPrimitive

Note:
============================================================================
Owned-Heap Wrapper Constants
============================================================================
:End Note

Note:
ALIGNED_HEADER_SIZE is the number of bytes reserved immediately before the
returned aligned pointer to store the original raw pointer that
MemoryLayout.allocate handed back. deallocate_aligned reads this slot to
recover the raw pointer and then calls the canonical deallocator.
:End Note

Constant ALIGNED_HEADER_SIZE as Integer is 8

Note:
LAYOUT_HEADER_SIZE is the size of the MemoryLayout owned-heap allocation
header that precedes every user data pointer. owned_heap_get_size walks
backwards through this offset to read the allocation ID stored at offset 0.
The value must match layout.runa's `header_size = 32` constant.
:End Note

Constant LAYOUT_HEADER_SIZE as Integer is 32

Note:
LAYOUT_REGISTRY_SIZE_OFFSET is the field offset of the recorded user size
within a registry entry (RegistryEntry layout, 56 bytes total, size at
offset 32 per layout.runa's documented entry structure).
:End Note

Constant LAYOUT_REGISTRY_SIZE_OFFSET as Integer is 32

Note:
============================================================================
Zero-Initialized Allocation
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "allocate_zeroed" takes size as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Allocate a TIER-3 owned-heap block and zero its user region before
        handing it back. Many callers want freshly zeroed memory for
        structure-shaped data (so that uninitialized field reads return 0
        deterministically) but pay the memset cost only when they actually
        want it; the un-zeroed path remains available via
        MemoryLayout.allocate. Returning 0 on either the allocate or the
        zero failure path keeps a simple ABI: callers test for zero, no
        secondary error channel is needed.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. Call MemoryLayout.allocate(size) to obtain a user pointer
               sitting behind the registry-tracked owned-heap header.
            2. If allocate returned 0, propagate the failure unchanged.
            3. Call MemoryCore.memory_zero(ptr, size) to clear exactly the
               size bytes of user region the caller asked for. Note that
               the allocator may have rounded up internally to 16 bytes
               for free-list metadata reuse, but we deliberately zero only
               the caller-visible size so that any allocator-private bytes
               beyond size remain in whatever state allocate left them.
            4. Return the user pointer.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        One owned-heap allocation plus one memory_zero pass. memory_zero is
        word-vectorised internally; the dominant cost is the allocate call,
        not the zero. Use MemoryLayout.allocate directly when the caller
        will overwrite the buffer immediately and the zero is wasted work.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        Zeroing the user region before returning prevents the new owner
        from observing stale heap contents from the previous allocation
        that reused this slot via the free-list path. This is a
        defence-in-depth measure - the allocator's free-list reuse path
        does not zero on free, so without this wrapper a caller asking for
        zeroed memory could inadvertently leak the previous owner's data.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let ptr be proc allocate from MemoryLayout with size

    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Zero exactly the caller-requested size (not the allocator's rounded-up size)
    Let dummy be proc memory_zero from MemoryCore with ptr, size

    Return ptr
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
Aligned Allocation (Stronger Than Default 8-Byte Alignment)
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "allocate_aligned" takes size as Integer, alignment as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Synthesise an owned-heap allocation whose returned pointer is aligned
        to an arbitrary power-of-two alignment stronger than the allocator's
        default. The technique is the standard over-allocate-and-align-up
        idiom: ask for (alignment-1) extra padding plus 8 bytes for a
        back-pointer header, align the user-visible pointer up inside that
        oversized block, and stash the original raw pointer in the 8 bytes
        immediately before the aligned pointer so deallocate_aligned can
        recover it.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. Compute the total allocation size:
                 extra_size = alignment - 1   (padding budget)
                 total_size = size + extra_size + ALIGNED_HEADER_SIZE
               The ALIGNED_HEADER_SIZE term reserves the 8 bytes that will
               hold the back-pointer header.
            2. Call MemoryLayout.allocate(total_size) for the raw pointer.
               Failure propagates as 0.
            3. Compute the candidate user pointer = raw_ptr + ALIGNED_HEADER_SIZE.
               This is the first byte past the reserved header.
            4. Round that candidate up to the requested alignment using the
               canonical PointerPrimitive.pointer_align_up. The padding
               budget reserved at step 1 guarantees the rounded pointer
               still lies inside the allocated block.
            5. Write the original raw pointer into the 8 bytes immediately
               preceding the aligned pointer (header_ptr = aligned_ptr - 8).
               deallocate_aligned reads this back.
            6. Return the aligned user pointer.

        Migration note (2026-05-18): the pre-migration source called a local
        align_pointer_up Process that was a literal duplicate of
        PointerPrimitive.pointer_align_up. The move into runtime rewrites
        the call to use the canonical primitive directly, eliminating the
        duplicate.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        One owned-heap allocation (the dominant cost) plus a single
        pointer-arithmetic round-up plus one pointer write. The padding
        overhead is at most alignment-1 bytes of wasted user region, which
        is the unavoidable cost of aligning over an allocator that returns
        8-byte-aligned pointers. For alignment values that the allocator
        already provides (alignment <= 8), prefer MemoryLayout.allocate
        directly to avoid the +8 header overhead.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        The back-pointer stored at aligned_ptr - 8 is private state used
        by deallocate_aligned. Callers who write into the byte region they
        receive must not write past size bytes in the negative direction;
        doing so would corrupt the back-pointer and cause deallocate_aligned
        to free an arbitrary address. The 8-byte gap is reserved for this
        purpose and is not part of the caller's usable size budget.
    @End Security_Scope

    Note: Reserve padding for alignment + 8 bytes for back-pointer header
    Let extra_size be alignment minus 1
    Let total_size be size plus extra_size plus ALIGNED_HEADER_SIZE

    Let raw_ptr be proc allocate from MemoryLayout with total_size

    If raw_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Compute aligned user pointer (first candidate past the header gap)
    Let ptr_plus_header be raw_ptr plus ALIGNED_HEADER_SIZE
    Let aligned_ptr be proc pointer_align_up from PointerPrimitive with ptr_plus_header, alignment

    Note: Store original raw pointer in the 8 bytes immediately before aligned_ptr
    Let header_ptr be aligned_ptr minus ALIGNED_HEADER_SIZE
    Let dummy be proc memory_set_pointer from MemoryCore with header_ptr, 0, raw_ptr

    Return aligned_ptr
End Process

Process called "deallocate_aligned" takes ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Free a buffer that was returned by allocate_aligned. The user pointer
        does not point at the start of the underlying owned-heap allocation,
        so we cannot pass it directly to MemoryLayout.deallocate; we first
        recover the original raw pointer from the 8-byte back-pointer header
        stored immediately before the user pointer.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL guard: return 0 on ptr == 0 (idempotent free).
            2. Compute header_ptr = ptr - ALIGNED_HEADER_SIZE.
            3. Read the raw pointer from offset 0 of the header slot
               (the value that allocate_aligned wrote at step 5).
            4. Call MemoryLayout.deallocate(raw_ptr) to release the
               underlying allocation, including the over-allocated padding
               and the back-pointer header.
            5. Return 1 on completion. We deliberately do not propagate
               MemoryLayout.deallocate's return value because the canonical
               deallocator returns 1 on success and 0 on argument error
               (ptr == 0), and we have already checked ptr above.
    @End Implementation

    @Security_Scope:
        Step 3 implicitly trusts that the 8 bytes before ptr contain the
        back-pointer that allocate_aligned wrote. Calling this function on
        any other pointer (one obtained from MemoryLayout.allocate
        directly, or a stack pointer, or a heap pointer from a different
        allocator) reads arbitrary memory and then attempts to free that
        arbitrary address. The contract is therefore: only call this with
        a pointer that allocate_aligned returned, and only call it once.
    @End Security_Scope

    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Recover original raw pointer from back-pointer header
    Let header_ptr be ptr minus ALIGNED_HEADER_SIZE
    Let original_ptr be proc memory_get_pointer from MemoryCore with header_ptr, 0

    Note: Free the original pointer through the canonical owned-heap deallocator
    Let dummy be proc deallocate from MemoryLayout with original_ptr
    Return 1
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
Registry-Aware User-Data Size Query
============================================================================
:End Note

Process called "owned_heap_get_size" takes ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning:
        Answer the question "how many bytes did the caller ask for when
        this user pointer was allocated?" for a pointer that was returned
        by MemoryLayout.allocate. The answer cannot be read directly from
        the in-memory header because layout.runa records total_size (header
        plus user region) there, not user_size; the user-requested size is
        only available from the registry entry inserted at allocation time.

        This Process replaces the pre-migration get_allocation_size, which
        assumed a `[size:8][user data]` header layout that MemoryLayout
        does NOT actually use. The pre-migration version read garbage from
        whatever byte happened to be 8 bytes before the user pointer (in
        the real layout, that location contains the third quadword of the
        header, namely total_size, not user size - and for back-pointer
        aligned allocations it contains the back-pointer itself, which is
        not a size at all). The fix is to consult the registry.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation:
        Steps:
            1. NULL guard: return 0 on ptr == 0.
            2. Compute header_ptr = ptr - LAYOUT_HEADER_SIZE. layout.runa
               places its 32-byte owned-heap header immediately before the
               user pointer it returns.
            3. Read alloc_id from offset 0 of the header (the first qword
               written by MemoryLayout.allocate at line 718/786).
            4. Look up the registry entry for that alloc_id via
               MemoryLayout.registry_lookup. Failed lookup (returned 0)
               means the pointer was either never registered, has already
               been removed (deallocated and the slot recycled), or did
               not originate from MemoryLayout.allocate. Return 0 in all
               those cases.
            5. Read the user size from offset LAYOUT_REGISTRY_SIZE_OFFSET
               (32) of the registry entry. layout.runa documents the
               registry entry layout: offset 32 holds size (allocation size
               in bytes).
            6. Return that size.

        Migration note (2026-05-18): this implementation is a from-scratch
        replacement of the pre-migration body, which read
            size = memory_get_integer(ptr - 8, 0)
        on the assumption of a wrong header layout. The new body walks the
        registry instead, which is the canonical source of truth for size
        information in the owned-heap subsystem.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints:
        Two memory reads (header alloc_id, registry size field) plus one
        linear-probe hash lookup. Constant time on average; worst case
        bounded by registry_capacity probes during lookup if the registry
        is heavily loaded. Callers who need this in a hot path should
        cache the result rather than re-querying.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope:
        The function reads 8 bytes at ptr - 32. If the caller passes a
        pointer that did NOT come from MemoryLayout.allocate (a stack
        pointer, an arena pointer, a pointer offset into the middle of an
        allocation), that read will return whatever bytes happen to live
        32 bytes before ptr, then registry_lookup will be called with that
        garbage value as alloc_id. The lookup is bounded (linear probe
        through the hash table) and side-effect-free, so the worst outcome
        is a 0 return - which is the right "I don't know" answer. The
        function therefore cannot crash on a bad pointer, only return 0.
    @End Security_Scope

    If ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Read alloc_id from the owned-heap header
    Let header_ptr be ptr minus LAYOUT_HEADER_SIZE
    Let alloc_id be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with header_ptr, 0

    Note: Look up the registry entry for this allocation
    Let entry_ptr be proc registry_lookup from MemoryLayout with alloc_id
    If entry_ptr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Read user-data size from the registry entry (offset 32 = size field)
    Let user_size be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with entry_ptr, LAYOUT_REGISTRY_SIZE_OFFSET
    Return user_size
End Process
